  <title>Description</title>
  <titlealts>
    <searchtitle>NHS Business Definition: CT Scan - Description</searchtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <body>
  <div>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_ct_scan">CT Scan</xref>
 is a 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_clinical_investigation">Clinical Investigation</xref>.        </p>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_ct_scan">CT Scan</xref>
 (<xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_ct_scan">Computerised Tomography Scan</xref>) uses X-rays and a computer to create detailed images of the inside of the body.        </p>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_ct_scan">CT Scan</xref>
 can be used to diagnose or monitor many different health conditions, including cancer and bone disease. It is often used to provide views of the body before another procedure takes place, such as a 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_biopsy">Biopsy</xref>
 or 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_radiotherapy">Radiotherapy</xref>
 treatment.        </p>
      <p>
For further information on 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_ct_scan">CT Scans</xref>, see the NHS website at: 
              <xref href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/ct-scan/"
               scope="external"
               format="html">CT scan</xref>.        </p>
  </div>
